abstract: A Trump appointment presages a purge at our intelligence agencies.
snippet: A Trump appointment presages a purge at our intelligence agencies.
lead_paragraph: It’s a really bad day at the office when the spooks are spooked. That’s what happened on Wednesday when President Trump announced that Richard Grenell, the ambassador to Germany, will become the acting director of national intelligence. Though Mr. Grenell is credited with effectively pushing the White House’s agenda on Iran and China, he has virtually no intelligence experience and is viewed as very partisan. This rattled the spy community and stoked fears that a purge may be coming, fears that seemed to be confirmed on Friday when Mr. Grenell ousted his office’s No. 2 official. In fact, our whole country should be spooked.

abstract: Biting commentary on racism in Germany featured prominently Monday among Carnival floats in western cities, hastily put together in the aftermath of a deadly far-right attack last week near Frankfurt.
snippet: Biting commentary on racism in Germany featured prominently Monday among Carnival floats in western cities, hastily put together in the aftermath of a deadly far-right attack last week near Frankfurt.
lead_paragraph: BERLIN — Biting commentary on racism in Germany featured prominently Monday among Carnival floats in western cities, hastily put together in the aftermath of a deadly far-right attack last week near Frankfurt.
headline_main: German Carnival Floats Take Aim at Racism in Wake of Attack
headline_print_headline: German Carnival Floats Take Aim at Racism in Wake of Attack

abstract: U.S. President Donald Trump vowed on Monday to boost trade ties between the United States and India, and said the United States was prepared to supply India with defense equipment ranging from drones to helicopters and missile systems.
snippet: U.S. President Donald Trump vowed on Monday to boost trade ties between the United States and India, and said the United States was prepared to supply India with defense equipment ranging from drones to helicopters and missile systems.
lead_paragraph: AHEMADABAD — U.S. President Donald Trump vowed on Monday to boost trade ties between the United States and India, and said the United States was prepared to supply India with defense equipment ranging from drones to helicopters and missile systems.
headline_main: Trump Says U.S. Keen to Boost Defense Equipment Sales to India
headline_print_headline: Trump Says U.S. Keen to Boost Defense Equipment Sales to India

abstract: With South Korea's defense minister due to meet his American counterpart on Monday in Washington, the U.S. military doubled down on calls for Seoul to pay more in defense costs, warning of the implications if a deal was not made soon.
snippet: With South Korea's defense minister due to meet his American counterpart on Monday in Washington, the U.S. military doubled down on calls for Seoul to pay more in defense costs, warning of the implications if a deal was not made soon.
lead_paragraph: SEOUL — With South Korea's defense minister due to meet his American counterpart on Monday in Washington, the U.S. military doubled down on calls for Seoul to pay more in defense costs, warning of the implications if a deal was not made soon.
headline_main: South Korea, U.S. Defense Chiefs to Meet Amid Unresolved Dispute on Cost-Sharing
headline_print_headline: South Korea, U.S. Defense Chiefs to Meet Amid Unresolved Dispute on Cost-Sharing

abstract: It’s now clear that the coronavirus epidemic was never going to be contained. What’s next?
snippet: It’s now clear that the coronavirus epidemic was never going to be contained. What’s next?
lead_paragraph: On Tuesday, Feb. 18, no Covid-19 cases had been reported in Iran. On Sunday, the government announced 43 cases and eight deaths. Some 152 cases (and at least three deaths) were confirmed in Italy on Sunday, up from three cases on Thursday. The number of infected people in South Korea jumped to 763 (and six deaths) in just days.

abstract: U.S. President Donald Trump will seek $2.5 billion from Congress to fight the coronavirus epidemic and U.S. and South Korean militaries are considering scaling back joint training as the virus spreads in Europe and the Middle East.

lead_paragraph: BEIJING/WASHINGTON — U.S. President Donald Trump will seek $2.5 billion from Congress to fight the coronavirus epidemic and U.S. and South Korean militaries are considering scaling back joint training as the virus spreads in Europe and the Middle East.
